const faqs = [{"question": "How long do pelvic floor exercises take to improve PE?", "answer": "Most men begin noticing improvements in ejaculatory control within 4–6 weeks of consistent practice. A 2014 study found that 82.5% of men with lifelong PE gained ejaculatory control after 12 weeks of pelvic floor rehabilitation. The key factor is consistency: exercises must be performed daily for the muscle adaptations to occur."}, {"question": "What's the difference between Kegels and reverse Kegels?", "answer": "Standard Kegels involve contracting (tightening) the pelvic floor muscles, the same muscles you use to stop urine midstream. This builds strength for voluntary ejaculation control. Reverse Kegels involve consciously relaxing and lengthening the pelvic floor muscles. This teaches you to release tension during sex, which is equally important because a chronically tense pelvic floor can actually trigger faster ejaculation."}, {"question": "Can I do pelvic floor exercises too much?", "answer": "Yes. Like any muscle, the pelvic floor can become fatigued or hypertonic (chronically tight) from overtraining. Signs of overdoing it include pelvic discomfort, urinary urgency, or worsening of PE symptoms. Follow the progressive schedule outlined in this guide and take rest days as recommended. If symptoms worsen, reduce frequency and consult a pelvic floor physiotherapist."}, {"question": "Should I do Kegels or reverse Kegels for PE?", "answer": "Both. A balanced approach is most effective. Standard Kegels build the strength needed to voluntarily inhibit ejaculation. Reverse Kegels teach you to release pelvic floor tension, which reduces the involuntary contractions that trigger ejaculation. Most PE exercise programs include both types."}, {"question": "Can women tell if I'm doing Kegel exercises?", "answer": "No. Pelvic floor exercises are internal and invisible. You can practice them anywhere (at your desk, while driving, or watching television) without anyone knowing. During sexual activity, your partner would only notice the positive results: improved control and confidence."}];

